@startuml
title NIST CSF 2.0 Applied to H&L Development

top to bottom direction

skinparam backgroundColor #FFFDF7
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam dpi 180
skinparam padding 20
skinparam nodesep 80
skinparam ranksep 90
skinparam roundcorner 25
skinparam ArrowThickness 2
skinparam ArrowFontSize 13
skinparam ArrowFontColor #1B1F2A
skinparam ArrowFontStyle bold
skinparam defaultTextAlignment center
skinparam linetype ortho

skinparam rectangle {
  BorderColor #2B2D42
  FontColor #1B1F2A
  FontSize 15
}

skinparam note {
  BackgroundColor #FFF4C2
  BorderColor #C59B00
  FontColor #3D3200
}

rectangle "GOVERN\nPolicies, roles, priorities,\nrisk communication" as GV #CDEBFF
rectangle "IDENTIFY\nAssets, dependencies,\nrisks, business context" as ID #C9F7D5
rectangle "PROTECT\nAccess control, encryption,\nplatform security, training" as PR #D8D0FF
rectangle "DETECT\nMonitoring, logging,\nanomaly detection" as DE #FFE3B3
rectangle "RESPOND\nTriage, containment,\ncommunication, mitigation" as RS #FFCAD4
rectangle "RECOVER\nRestoration, validation,\nlessons learned, resilience" as RC #BEEAF9

note right of GV
Applies across all CSF functions
end note

note right of ID
HLD examples:
- login portals
- cloud databases
- source code repositories
- API keys
- third-party services
end note

note right of PR
HLD examples:
- MFA
- rate limiting
- CAPTCHA
- encryption
- branch protection
- secret management
end note

note right of DE
HLD examples:
- centralized logging
- SIEM alerts
- abnormal query detection
- suspicious repository activity
end note

note right of RS
HLD examples:
- incident triage
- containment actions
- credential revocation
- stakeholder communication
- deployment rollback
end note

note right of RC
HLD examples:
- validated backups
- prioritized restoration
- recovery communication
- continuous improvement
end note

GV -[#2A9D8F,thickness=3]-> ID : Direction
ID -[#5E60CE,thickness=3]-> PR : Safeguards
PR -[#F4A261,thickness=3]-> DE : Visibility
DE -[#E76F51,thickness=3]-> RS : Response
RS -[#457B9D,thickness=3]-> RC : Restoration
RC -[#8D5A97,thickness=3]-> ID : Lessons learned

GV -[hidden]down-> ID
ID -[hidden]down-> PR
PR -[hidden]down-> DE
DE -[hidden]down-> RS
RS -[hidden]down-> RC

legend left
|= Arrow |= Meaning |
|<color:#2A9D8F>Direction</color> | Governance sets security direction, priorities, and accountability. |
|<color:#5E60CE>Safeguards</color> | Identified assets and risks shape the safeguards to apply. |
|<color:#F4A261>Visibility</color> | Protective controls improve monitoring and detection visibility. |
|<color:#E76F51>Response</color> | Detected incidents trigger triage, containment, and communication. |
|<color:#457B9D>Restoration</color> | Response actions move the organization into service restoration. |
|<color:#8D5A97>Lessons learned</color> | Recovery lessons update the risk picture for future planning. |
endlegend
@enduml
